data.value:
Orion is a prominent constellation that’s visible throughout the world. As such, it’s one of the most recognizable constellations. Orion is visible in the night sky from November to February. The brightest stars in Orion are Betelgeuse and Rigel, which you can see labeled in the picture to the right.
The constellation is named after Orion, a hunter in Greek mythology. According to one version of the myth, Orion was a gigantic and supernaturally strong hunter. He was born to Euryale, a gorgon, and Poseidon (Neptune), god the sea. In this version, the myth speaks of Gaia’s (the god of the Earth) rage at Orion, who declared he would kill every animal on Earth. The angry goddess decided to have Orion killed by poisoning him with the sting of a scorpion. In consolation, Zeus (the king of the gods) had him immortalized in the sky, to forever continue his hunt.
Beyond any myths, this constellation has proven a fertile hunting ground for extra-solar planets, or exoplanets. Exoplanets are planets beyond our solar system. Investigations are ongoing, but many ‘planet-sized objects’ have been found near the stars of Orion.
